15.2   Terminal Nerves of the Brachial Plexus I
The cords of the brachial plexus give rise to the major peripheral nerves of the upper limb.
give rise to three major peripheral nerves. Place a probe or a finger underneath these cords and nerves to isolate them, and notice that they form the shape of the letter “M”     .
On the prosection, confirm that the lateral and medial cords

Identify the musculocutaneous nerve (C5-C6)* as the continuation of the lateral cord. 
Identify the median nerve (C6-T1)* in the middle     , formed by contributions from both the lateral and medial cord.
Identify the ulnar nerve (C8-T1) as the continuation of the medial cord. 
These nerves, with few exceptions     , innervate the muscles of the anterior compartment of the arm, the anterior compartment of the forearm, and the hand, respectively.
* Take note!! A nerve derived from the brachial plexus does not necessarily take fibres from all the levels contained in the parent nerve. Here you see this is true of the musculocutaneous and median nerves.
I’ve highlighted this in the diagram on this slide, in red.
I’ll get to the exceptions in the next lab, but for now, learn these basic relationships between the 3 nerves and their targets, in general.
